\title{gridmorph: Raster-Native Shape Indices and Morphological Operators}
\description{
Shape/compactness/dispersal indices for a single terra SpatRaster,
treating a whole shape - however many disjoint patches or holes it has -
as one combined shape, the same way \code{shapeindices} treats a
MULTIPOLYGON. The shape itself is derived directly from the raster's own
values (non-\code{NA}, non-zero cells); a \code{weighted} argument on every index
controls whether those values are also used as a density/mass field
(\code{TRUE}, default) or ignored beyond defining the shape (\code{FALSE}). Also
exposes morphological operators (erosion, dilation, opening, closing,
top-hat, bottom-hat) directly on \code{terra} SpatRaster objects.
}
\section{Planar rasters only}{
Every index in this package assumes \code{rast} uses PLANAR (projected)
coordinates. This is \emph{not} because area, distance, or perimeter can't be
computed correctly on geographic (longitude/latitude) data in
general - \code{terra}'s own \code{\link[terra:expanse]{terra::expanse()}}, \code{\link[terra:perim]{terra::perim()}}, and
\code{\link[terra:distance]{terra::distance()}} all do that correctly, via geodesic math, even in a
geographic CRS (see \code{terra}'s own documentation, which explicitly notes
that area is often \emph{better} computed directly in longitude/latitude than
by reprojecting first). The real problem is narrower: this package's own
point-based geometry - line-crossing tests for \code{gm_convexity_index()},
pairwise-distance accumulation for \code{gm_span_index()}/
\code{gm_radial_concentration_index()}, moment-tensor calculations for
\code{gm_moment_of_inertia_index()} and its relatives, and minimum-enclosing-
circle fitting for \code{gm_reock_index()}/\code{gm_detour_index()} - works
directly in raw x/y coordinate space throughout, treating it as
Cartesian, and is not yet geodesic-aware. Every index function checks
this and \strong{errors} if \code{rast} has a real geographic CRS - reproject to a
suitable projected CRS first (e.g. via \code{\link[terra:project]{terra::project()}}). A raster
with no CRS at all is allowed (warned about, not blocked) and treated as
already planar, matching the common case of a purely synthetic or
abstract grid with no real-world geographic meaning. The morphological
operators (\code{erode()}, \code{dilate()}, \code{opening()}, \code{closing()}, \code{tophat()},
\code{bottomhat()}) are the one exception - they only reason about cell
adjacency via a structuring-element kernel, never physical distance, so
they work identically regardless of CRS.
